WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.336
<i>Previously on "The Rookie"...</i>
Your dad is
a hell of a guy.

00:02.336 --> 00:02.377
Maybe...you and I could
grab dinner sometime.

00:03.003 --> 00:04.171
Maybe...you and I could
grab dinner sometime.

00:04.963 --> 00:06.215
That'd be great.

00:06.215 --> 00:07.466
Mm.
I bet your lovely wife

00:07.466 --> 00:09.176
is out there listening, too,
isn't she?

00:09.176 --> 00:10.511
I'm gonna
report your husband

00:10.511 --> 00:11.887
to the California
state bar.

00:11.887 --> 00:13.680
I'm gonna have
his law license revoked

00:13.680 --> 00:15.432
for betraying the trust
of a client.

00:15.432 --> 00:17.100
Lucy: Oh, my God.
Are you going to propose?

00:17.100 --> 00:18.310
I'm in love with you.

00:18.310 --> 00:20.062
Thank God. 'Cause I'm
in love with you, too.

00:20.062 --> 00:21.772
Bailey.
Jason.

00:21.772 --> 00:23.607
I'm John Nolan, her boyfriend.
And you are?

00:23.607 --> 00:25.234
Uh, her husband.

00:27.486 --> 00:30.113
[ Chuckles softly ]

00:30.113 --> 00:32.074
Uh, you mean ex‐husband.

00:32.074 --> 00:34.117
Uh, I do not.
[ Chuckles ]

00:34.117 --> 00:36.745
Long time, babe. I guess
she didn't mention me, huh?

00:36.745 --> 00:38.789
I mean, I get it. You know,
it's ‐‐ it's embarrassing.

00:38.789 --> 00:40.916
A husband in prison.
[ Chuckles ]

00:40.916 --> 00:42.376
Bailey?

00:42.376 --> 00:44.753
You're weren't supposed to
get out for another two years.

00:44.753 --> 00:47.089
Good behavior. I‐I can
hardly believe it myself.

00:47.089 --> 00:50.467
Oh. Look. Uh, clearly
I'm interrupting here.

00:50.467 --> 00:53.178
Um, I'm sorry. I didn't realize
you were seeing someone.

00:53.178 --> 00:54.721
Uh, it's nice
to meet you, John.

00:54.721 --> 00:56.306
You, uh,
be good to her, huh?

00:56.306 --> 00:59.059
My wife deserves the best.

00:59.059 --> 01:00.435
It's good to see you.

01:01.770 --> 01:03.230
Sorry.

01:09.736 --> 01:13.699
♪♪

01:13.699 --> 01:15.200
So you're married.

01:17.911 --> 01:20.664
And you didn't tell me.

01:20.664 --> 01:22.624
[ Voice breaking ]
I‐I have to go.

01:22.624 --> 01:24.084
Bailey.

01:24.084 --> 01:26.211
♪♪

01:26.211 --> 01:27.212
Bailey.

01:27.212 --> 01:34.678
♪♪

01:38.223 --> 01:40.892
[ Grease sizzling,
utensil scraping ]

01:42.603 --> 01:44.604
Smells great. Salmon?

01:44.604 --> 01:45.689
And eggs.

01:45.689 --> 01:47.858
I'm not really
a breakfast person.

01:47.858 --> 01:50.902
I know. It's for Kojo.
Excuse me.

01:50.902 --> 01:53.488
Salmon and eggs.
For your dog.

01:53.488 --> 01:55.866
Well, not <i>every</i> day.
I have to watch his cholesterol.

01:55.866 --> 01:56.950
[ Chuckles ]

01:56.950 --> 01:58.243
[ Whistles ]

01:58.243 --> 01:59.369
Oh!

01:59.369 --> 02:00.996
There he is!
Who's a good dog?

02:00.996 --> 02:02.372
Who's the <i>best</i> dog?

02:02.372 --> 02:04.207
Tricia will be here at 11:00
to give you a walk.

02:04.207 --> 02:05.584
Ready to go?

02:05.584 --> 02:06.710
[ Dog barking ]
[ Gasps ]

02:06.710 --> 02:09.171
Whoa! Hey!
Kojo, knock it off.

02:09.171 --> 02:12.299
He's just a little territorial
around his food.

02:12.299 --> 02:13.842
How long have you had him?
A year.

02:13.842 --> 02:15.886
He was Lucy's,
but she couldn't keep him.

02:15.886 --> 02:17.220
[ Dog barking and growling ]

02:17.220 --> 02:19.014
[ Monitor beeping,
dog barking ]

02:19.014 --> 02:21.016
Kojo! Unh‐unh!

02:21.016 --> 02:23.769
[ Monitor beeps ]
Voice: <i>Armed stay. Exit now.</i>

02:23.769 --> 02:25.187
[ Barking continues ]

02:25.187 --> 02:27.606
Kojo! Hey, hey, hey!

02:27.606 --> 02:29.232
I am ‐‐ I'm sorry.

02:29.232 --> 02:31.026
Look, it's your first time
sleeping over,

02:31.026 --> 02:33.236
and he's just not
used to you being here.

02:33.236 --> 02:36.031
Here. Why don't you
just put your hand out?

02:36.031 --> 02:38.742
It's okay.
The alarm is about to set.

02:38.742 --> 02:41.078
We can do it another day.

02:41.078 --> 02:42.579
[ Dog whining ]
Sure.

02:42.579 --> 02:45.582
Hey. Be good.
Alright?

02:45.582 --> 02:47.167
[ Door closes ]

02:47.167 --> 02:48.877
Nolan: Why didn't Bailey
just tell me?

02:48.877 --> 02:52.005
I mean, if it's complicated,
just say so. I'll understand.

02:52.005 --> 02:54.508
Is it because of the ex‐con
thing and I'm a cop?

02:54.508 --> 02:57.260
Who doesn't have a criminal
in their family?

02:57.260 --> 02:59.346
It does not get much more
embarrassing than Pete.
Mm.

02:59.346 --> 03:01.348
And I'm ‐‐ Oh, I'm spinning out.
I‐I'm gonna stop.

03:01.348 --> 03:02.891
Well, of course
you're spinning out.

03:02.891 --> 03:04.810
I mean, she's been lying to you
this whole time.

03:04.810 --> 03:06.937
And technically I didn't ask
if she was married.

03:06.937 --> 03:09.064
Yeah, but she knows
you were serious about her.

03:09.064 --> 03:11.358
Every day that she did not
tell you about her husband

03:11.358 --> 03:13.485
is a day
that she lied to you.

03:13.485 --> 03:15.404
Do you know
<i>why</i> he was in jail?

03:15.404 --> 03:18.073
No. No clue.
Alright.

03:18.073 --> 03:21.118
Call my skip tracer,
have him run this Jason guy.

03:21.118 --> 03:23.245
[ <i>Line ringing</i> ]
You got a lot of questions.

03:23.245 --> 03:24.913
You need to start
getting answers.

03:24.913 --> 03:27.249
Randy: <i>Skip tracer Randy! That's</i>
<i>me! What can I do you for?</i>

03:27.249 --> 03:30.293
Whoa. Hey, Randy.
It's, uh, John Nolan.

03:30.293 --> 03:31.837
I need you
to run a name for me.

03:31.837 --> 03:33.588
When's Wesley gonna hear back
from the state bar?

03:33.588 --> 03:37.551
Ugh. Any day now. He hasn't
slept the last few nights.

03:37.551 --> 03:39.886
What happened?

03:39.886 --> 03:41.263
They suspended my license.

03:41.263 --> 03:42.931
I can't practice law
for six months.

03:42.931 --> 03:45.183
No. That's insane!

03:45.183 --> 03:46.393
You were under duress.

03:46.393 --> 03:47.769
They have to take that
into account.

03:47.769 --> 03:49.020
Can you appeal it?

03:49.020 --> 03:50.313
Look. It won't make
a difference.

03:50.313 --> 03:51.773
I broke client confidentiality.

03:51.773 --> 03:54.317
The state bar takes that
very seriously.

03:54.317 --> 03:56.236
I‐It's not even about
the suspension itself.

03:56.236 --> 03:58.405
I'm on a list now of lawyers
who have embezzled

03:58.405 --> 03:59.865
from their clients,
taken bribes.

03:59.865 --> 04:02.159
For the rest of my career,
whenever somebody looks me up,

04:02.159 --> 04:04.119
they'll see that
I have been censured.

04:04.119 --> 04:05.454
I'm sorry.

04:06.621 --> 04:08.498
[ Softly ] Yeah.

04:08.498 --> 04:10.959
[ Horn honks,
indistinct shouting ]

04:10.959 --> 04:12.961
Alright. Thanks.
I'll be in touch.

04:12.961 --> 04:14.463
What did his
parole officer say?

04:14.463 --> 04:16.756
Same thing ‐‐
he got out on good behavior.

04:16.756 --> 04:18.758
Unless he violates parole,
he's a free man.

04:18.758 --> 04:20.635
‐And you don't believe it?
‐Oh, I believe it.

04:20.635 --> 04:22.304
I'm sure he was charming,

04:22.304 --> 04:25.098
knew all the guards' birthdays,
asked after their kids,

04:25.098 --> 04:27.225
made everyone handcrafted gifts
at Christmas.

04:27.225 --> 04:28.727
Ah, he sounds...awful?

04:28.727 --> 04:30.645
It's all roses
and trips to Paris

04:30.645 --> 04:33.857
until you dare disagree
with him, and then...

04:33.857 --> 04:35.233
This is how it was.

04:35.233 --> 04:37.152
I would try and tell people
who he really was ‐‐

04:37.152 --> 04:40.864
they guy they never saw ‐‐
and I'd sound insane.

04:40.864 --> 04:42.783
Okay. Well, you know,
it's all behind you now.

04:42.783 --> 04:45.702
You got to focus on the future.
First up, get that divorce.

04:45.702 --> 04:47.913
I tried! For two years!

04:47.913 --> 04:49.247
He would go along with it,

04:49.247 --> 04:51.374
pretending to engage
in the negotiations,

04:51.374 --> 04:53.502
and then he'd cut off contact
for months.

04:53.502 --> 04:55.128
And just when I had given up,

04:55.128 --> 04:56.505
he would come back
with some new demand,

04:56.505 --> 04:58.507
and we would start this process
all over again.

04:58.507 --> 05:01.343
[ Cellphone beeping ]
[ Sighs ]

05:01.343 --> 05:03.178
Fraud alert?

05:03.178 --> 05:07.516
Someone just charged $2,000
on my credit card.

05:07.516 --> 05:09.851
[ Gasps ] It's Jason.

05:09.851 --> 05:11.520
Or it's more likely
that some rando

05:11.520 --> 05:13.230
cloned your card,
don't you think?

05:13.230 --> 05:16.316
No. No. I‐I‐I‐I‐I don't ‐‐
I don't know. Maybe ‐‐

05:16.316 --> 05:19.110
Hey. Hey!
Do not spin out.

05:19.110 --> 05:22.364
You go into shock inside of
a burning building, people die.

05:22.364 --> 05:25.784
Right now your house
is a little on fire.

05:25.784 --> 05:28.411
So focus up.
What's your plan?

05:28.411 --> 05:32.374
Okay. Uh...call Jason
to the station.

05:32.374 --> 05:35.001
My turf, surrounded
by my friends.

05:35.001 --> 05:37.504
Show him that
I'm not afraid anymore.

05:37.504 --> 05:38.922
Tell him
I want a divorce.

05:40.090 --> 05:42.884
So, how's it going
with Ashley?

05:42.884 --> 05:45.971
Good. Although there was
some weirdness this morning.

05:45.971 --> 05:47.722
I don't think
she likes Kojo.

05:47.722 --> 05:49.015
So you broke up with her?

05:49.015 --> 05:50.725
That's ‐‐ That's too bad.
I liked her.

05:50.725 --> 05:52.727
Since when? Last time
we talked about her,

05:52.727 --> 05:54.271
you gave me grief
because she's a lifeguard.

05:54.271 --> 05:56.439
Okay. Look.
I've never really considered

05:56.439 --> 05:57.774
lifeguarding a career.

05:57.774 --> 05:59.276
Okay. You see,
and that is what's called

05:59.276 --> 06:00.610
"Baywatch"‐based
implicit bias.

06:00.610 --> 06:02.153
[ Laughing ] What?!
Ashley went through

06:02.153 --> 06:04.698
rigorous training at the fire
academy to become a lifeguard.

06:04.698 --> 06:06.741
Okay. My bad. But you know what?
It is a moot point

06:06.741 --> 06:09.911
because she doesn't like Kojo,
first of his name,

06:09.911 --> 06:12.539
king of canines,
destroyer of chew toys.

06:12.539 --> 06:15.709
So, clearly,
Ashley has got to go.

06:15.709 --> 06:17.669
[ Radio chatter ]

06:17.669 --> 06:18.920
Check out
Mister Dollar Sign.

06:18.920 --> 06:22.257
Hand‐to‐hand transfer.
Classic 11532.

06:22.257 --> 06:25.051
[ Siren chirps ]

06:25.051 --> 06:26.636
Hey.
You are way too young

06:26.636 --> 06:28.346
to be throwing your life away
dealing drugs.

06:28.346 --> 06:29.931
Show me your hands.
Hey. No!

06:29.931 --> 06:31.641
Hey! Stop!
Control, 7‐Adam‐100.

06:31.641 --> 06:33.768
We got a foot pursuit
southbound, Citrus at Olympic.

06:33.768 --> 06:35.604
Black male. Green pants.
Black hoodie.

06:35.604 --> 06:37.439
Hey! Get back here!

06:37.439 --> 06:38.565
[ Grunts ]

06:38.565 --> 06:39.900
Put your hands
behind your head.

06:39.900 --> 06:41.610
Okay.
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

06:41.610 --> 06:43.987
♪♪

06:43.987 --> 06:46.031
[ Engine sputtering ]
Control ‐‐

06:46.031 --> 06:48.617
[ Engine sputtering ]

06:48.617 --> 06:50.201
What the hell?

06:50.201 --> 06:52.412
7‐Adam‐100. We've got
a possible Code 1000.

06:52.412 --> 06:53.788
Repeat ‐‐ Code 1000.

06:53.788 --> 06:55.415
Single‐engine fixed wing
in distress, headed ‐‐

06:55.415 --> 06:57.542
[ Crash and explosion
in distance ]

06:57.542 --> 06:59.085
♪♪

06:59.085 --> 07:00.754
Ohh. 7‐Adam‐15.

07:00.754 --> 07:04.716
A plane is down. 1200 block of
Langston. Send fire and RAs.

07:04.716 --> 07:06.468
[ Engine revs, siren wails ]

07:06.468 --> 07:09.638
♪ Blurry vision, can't see ♪

07:09.638 --> 07:12.515
♪ Heavy breathing, and it's
standing right in front of me ♪

07:12.515 --> 07:15.727
♪ I can't move, I can't stand ♪

07:15.727 --> 07:21.232
♪ I gotta, gotta, gotta, gotta,
gotta, gotta get away ♪

07:21.232 --> 07:24.027
♪ Get away ♪

07:24.027 --> 07:25.487
♪ I gotta get away ♪

07:25.487 --> 07:27.572
[ Gasps ]
You take the car.

07:27.572 --> 07:28.907
Yeah.

07:28.907 --> 07:30.158
♪ Get away ♪

07:30.158 --> 07:31.493
‐Hey.
‐Get me out of here, please.

07:31.493 --> 07:33.161
Get me out of here.
Just relax. Relax.

07:33.161 --> 07:34.579
Right now I just
need you to breathe.

07:34.579 --> 07:36.039
What's your name?
Jade.

07:36.039 --> 07:37.874
Okay, Jade.
Help is on the way, alright?

07:37.874 --> 07:40.085
Bailey, this is Jade.
Bailey's gonna help you out.

07:40.085 --> 07:42.045
She's one of the best.
Bailey: Okay.

07:42.045 --> 07:43.838
We're gonna get you out of there
in no time, Jade.

07:43.838 --> 07:45.840
Tell me ‐‐ are you
having trouble breathing?
No.

07:45.840 --> 07:47.592
Did you hit your head
when you crashed?

07:47.592 --> 07:50.720
‐I think so.
‐Okay. Come on.

07:50.720 --> 07:52.889
[ Saw buzzing ]

07:52.889 --> 07:55.433
[ Siren wailing,
tires screech ]

07:55.433 --> 07:58.436
♪♪

07:58.436 --> 07:59.813
What's the situation?

07:59.813 --> 08:01.815
Harper: We're still assessing.
The driver got the worst of it.

08:01.815 --> 08:03.108
The flipped cars were empty.

08:03.108 --> 08:05.151
‐And the pilot?
‐I don't know.

08:05.151 --> 08:09.739
♪♪

08:13.410 --> 08:16.955
There's no pilot.
Explains why it crashed.

08:21.000 --> 08:22.877
Man:
<i>Control, this is Air 7.</i>

08:22.877 --> 08:24.379
<i>We're on scene at that</i>
<i>fixed‐wing code 1000.</i>

08:24.379 --> 08:25.755
<i>Requesting restricted air space</i>
<i>with half‐a‐mile perimeter.</i>

08:25.755 --> 08:27.132
Whoever was flying this plane
must've left prints.

08:27.132 --> 08:30.343
I will dust and run them
on my Mobile ID.

08:30.343 --> 08:32.637
[ Indistinct conversations ]

08:32.637 --> 08:34.222
[ Camera shutter clicking ]

08:37.058 --> 08:39.269
Uh...guys?

08:39.269 --> 08:40.478
There's gold back here.

08:40.478 --> 08:43.231
Like a couple dozen
Fort Knox‐size bars.

08:43.231 --> 08:44.941
[ ID device beeps ]

08:44.941 --> 08:46.317
And it gets weirder.

08:46.317 --> 08:49.195
The fingerprints I just pulled
match a Levi Lincoln,

08:49.195 --> 08:50.947
who is currently an inmate

08:50.947 --> 08:53.575
at the California
Correctional Facility.

08:53.575 --> 08:56.077
So an escaped convict
stole a plane

08:56.077 --> 08:57.787
and crashed it in the middle
of Mid‐Wilshire?

08:57.787 --> 08:59.789
Don't forget
the 200 pounds of gold.

08:59.789 --> 09:01.124
I'll call the warden.

09:01.124 --> 09:03.835
Levi Lincoln? Why does
that name sound familiar?

09:03.835 --> 09:05.086
[ Gasps ] Oh, wait!

09:05.086 --> 09:08.548
Uh ‐‐ Uh, that millionaire
who killed his wife.

09:08.548 --> 09:10.925
Yeah, that narrows it down
less than you'd think.

09:10.925 --> 09:12.427
Nolan: No. Uh, no.
I remember. Yeah.

09:12.427 --> 09:15.388
It was a particularly brutal
murder, but Levi's lawyer

09:15.388 --> 09:17.057
got the charges knocked down
to manslaughter.

09:17.057 --> 09:19.225
Yeah, looks like
he only got 10 years.

09:19.225 --> 09:20.518
This makes no sense.

09:20.518 --> 09:22.979
How does an inmate at
a maximum security prison

09:22.979 --> 09:25.190
break out with a plane
full of gold?

09:25.190 --> 09:28.359
He didn't. The prison says
Levi Lincoln's still there.

09:28.359 --> 09:30.612
Why are his prints
in the plane?

09:30.612 --> 09:31.905
Harper, Nolan,
go to the prison.

09:31.905 --> 09:33.281
Find out what the hell's
going on.

09:33.281 --> 09:34.866
Right.

09:37.118 --> 09:39.788
Uh, give me a minute?

09:39.788 --> 09:41.331
Yeah.

09:41.331 --> 09:44.918
Woman:
Yes, sir. Yes, sir.

09:44.918 --> 09:46.544
I know
you're angry with me.

09:46.544 --> 09:48.797
Oh, I haven't really
gotten to angry yet.

09:48.797 --> 09:50.256
I think
I'm still in shock.

09:50.256 --> 09:51.966
I am so sorry.

09:51.966 --> 09:53.676
I ‐‐ It was
a nightmare marriage.

09:53.676 --> 09:55.845
I tried to divorce him,
but Jason fought me on it.

09:55.845 --> 09:58.181
Then he got arrested
and went to prison ‐‐
Bailey.

09:58.181 --> 10:00.975
I was so tired of fighting him
that I just walked away.

10:00.975 --> 10:04.395
Bailey, stop. I'm not angry
because you're married.

10:04.395 --> 10:08.399
I'm ‐‐ I mean, yes, I am.
Of course I am.

10:08.399 --> 10:10.944
I'm just more upset that
you didn't trust me enough

10:10.944 --> 10:13.196
to be honest about
something this important.

10:13.196 --> 10:14.364
Mnh.

10:14.364 --> 10:15.949
And I just don't...

10:15.949 --> 10:18.034
know how to move forward
from this.

10:18.034 --> 10:20.745
♪♪

10:20.745 --> 10:22.872
I got ‐‐ I got to go.

10:22.872 --> 10:29.963
♪♪

10:29.963 --> 10:32.423
You got to give him time.
I mean, he just found out.

10:32.423 --> 10:35.426
I know.
But I can't lose him over this.

10:35.426 --> 10:36.803
Bailey.

10:37.846 --> 10:40.890
Uh, thanks
for reaching out.

10:40.890 --> 10:42.892
Look, we are not
reconnecting here.

10:42.892 --> 10:44.394
I want a divorce.

10:44.394 --> 10:46.020
I get that you're pissed at me,
alright?

10:46.020 --> 10:47.981
And you ‐‐ you deserve to be.
But listen.

10:47.981 --> 10:50.233
Ever since I got out,
I‐I've been trying to find you

10:50.233 --> 10:54.028
so that I could apologize
for the man that I was.

10:54.028 --> 10:55.822
And could I ‐‐
could I buy you lunch

10:55.822 --> 10:57.907
and we could talk about it?
No, Jason.

10:57.907 --> 11:00.785
We're talking here, because
this is where I feel safe.

11:00.785 --> 11:02.120
Of course. Yeah.

11:02.120 --> 11:04.539
Oh. [ Chuckles ] Hi.
[ Chuckles ]

11:04.539 --> 11:06.624
Uh, I'm ‐‐ I'm Jason.

11:06.624 --> 11:10.253
Also known as the worst husband
in recorded history.

11:10.253 --> 11:12.630
I'm Sharon.
It's nice to meet you.

11:12.630 --> 11:15.592
So, what are you doing
here i‐in L. A.?

11:15.592 --> 11:16.968
What do you want?

11:16.968 --> 11:20.471
For you to be happy.
Um...

11:22.223 --> 11:24.934
What's that?

11:24.934 --> 11:26.394
Divorce papers.

11:26.394 --> 11:28.646
I'm sorry.
I was so stubborn.

11:28.646 --> 11:30.773
I‐I thought that I could
make you love me again.

11:30.773 --> 11:34.068
But I, uh, ruined
everything, didn't I?

11:36.321 --> 11:39.574
Anyway, uh, legally,
'cause I'm your spouse,

11:39.574 --> 11:41.576
I‐I can't hand these
to you directly.

11:41.576 --> 11:44.787
So, uh, Sharon,
if you would be so kind.

11:46.706 --> 11:49.167
Um...
I'll see you around.

11:52.212 --> 11:54.255
Well, he's giving you
everything you want.

11:58.259 --> 12:00.094
Wes.

12:00.094 --> 12:02.639
James. Hey.
What are you doing here?

12:02.639 --> 12:05.850
Ugh. A kid I mentor
just got arrested.

12:05.850 --> 12:08.519
Hey, uh, maybe you
could represent him.

12:08.519 --> 12:10.313
[ Chuckles softly ]

12:10.313 --> 12:12.357
Look, I‐I wish I could,

12:12.357 --> 12:14.651
but my license just
got suspended for six months

12:14.651 --> 12:16.361
because of
the Elijah Stone thing.

12:16.361 --> 12:18.321
That's tough, man.
I'm ‐‐ I'm ‐‐ I'm sorry.

12:18.321 --> 12:19.447
Thanks.

12:19.447 --> 12:21.574
So ‐‐ So what are you
gonna do?

12:21.574 --> 12:24.661
Well, right now I'm debating
which bar to get drunk at.

12:24.661 --> 12:26.496
Well, you should not
do that alone.

12:26.496 --> 12:28.831
Text me when you decide, and
I'll come meet you after this.

12:28.831 --> 12:30.041
Hm.

12:30.041 --> 12:32.961
Hey, I‐I heard what happened.
I'm so sorry.

12:32.961 --> 12:34.629
I appreciate that.

12:34.629 --> 12:36.381
I'll text you.

12:36.381 --> 12:38.341
So, where's Tyler?

12:38.341 --> 12:40.134
Processing.

12:40.134 --> 12:42.136
I couldn't get ahold of
his mother, so when he said

12:42.136 --> 12:44.347
he knew you, I‐I‐I thought
it was worth a shot.

12:44.347 --> 12:46.391
Yeah. Tyler's in
a bad situation at home.

12:46.391 --> 12:48.518
His father's incarcerated,
and his mother...

12:48.518 --> 12:50.645
she has problems
of her own.

12:50.645 --> 12:52.063
So you caught him dealing?

12:52.063 --> 12:54.232
Yeah, I'm afraid so.

12:58.027 --> 13:00.196
[ Sighs ] What the hell
was he thinking?

13:00.196 --> 13:02.031
You know, I have a little bit
of leeway here.

13:02.031 --> 13:04.325
I can cite him on a JCR,
which would mean

13:04.325 --> 13:07.370
he would go home today
until his court date.

13:07.370 --> 13:09.539
That would be huge.
I mean, I ‐‐ [ Sighs ]

13:09.539 --> 13:11.291
I just started working
with this kid.

13:11.291 --> 13:13.376
He's ‐‐ He's veering
close to the edge,

13:13.376 --> 13:17.672
but if we lose him to the system
now, he's lost forever.

13:18.756 --> 13:20.466
Okay. Yeah.
I'll cite him out.

13:20.466 --> 13:23.386
[ Buzzer sounds ]
I hate this prison.

13:23.386 --> 13:25.263
Are there prisons
you <i>don't</i> hate?

13:25.263 --> 13:27.223
All the ones
I haven't almost died in.

13:27.223 --> 13:29.767
At least we're not here
to see Oscar.
Why? Why?

13:29.767 --> 13:31.144
Why do you always jinx us?

13:31.144 --> 13:33.229
I‐It's like a compulsion
with you.

13:33.229 --> 13:34.772
[ Buzzer sounds ]
I ‐‐

13:34.772 --> 13:37.275
Levi Lincoln.
I am Detective Harper.

13:37.275 --> 13:40.028
This is Officer Nolan.
We have some questions for you.

13:40.028 --> 13:41.446
About what?

13:41.446 --> 13:45.450
Have you ever flown a Cessna,
tail number N97741?

13:45.450 --> 13:48.369
How the hell would I know?
I own a lot of planes.

13:48.369 --> 13:51.205
Okay, well, this particular
plane crashed this morning

13:51.205 --> 13:52.832
with your fingerprints
inside.

13:52.832 --> 13:54.834
[ Exhales sharply ]
Well, that's impossible.

13:54.834 --> 13:57.462
You got that right. You've been
incarcerated for 36 months,

13:57.462 --> 13:59.464
and those fingerprints
are fresh.

13:59.464 --> 14:00.757
So what the hell?

14:00.757 --> 14:02.550
I mean, that sounds
like a "you" problem.

14:02.550 --> 14:05.053
No, no. I think ‐‐ I think
something funny is going on.

14:05.053 --> 14:06.721
‐I think it's him.
‐I agree.

14:06.721 --> 14:09.223
Um, what is your wife's
name?

14:09.223 --> 14:10.475
Linda ‐‐

14:13.311 --> 14:14.687
I'm not married.

14:16.689 --> 14:18.024
And I need to see a lawyer.

14:18.024 --> 14:20.276
Sir, you're a federal inmate,
and I have every right

14:20.276 --> 14:22.528
to inspect
your person, so...

14:22.528 --> 14:28.743
♪♪

14:28.743 --> 14:31.162
Plastic‐surgery scars.

14:31.162 --> 14:35.458
How much did Levi Lincoln
pay you to do his time?

14:35.458 --> 14:36.876
$5 million up front

14:36.876 --> 14:39.003
and $5 million upon
the completion of his sentence.

14:39.003 --> 14:41.589
Oh, you ‐‐ you should've held
out for more. The guy's loaded.

14:41.589 --> 14:45.176
Prisoners are fingerprinted
upon arrival, so someone here

14:45.176 --> 14:47.970
had to have helped you and Levi
pull this off. Who was it?

14:47.970 --> 14:50.223
If I tell you that,
I'll be dead by sundown.

14:50.223 --> 14:52.058
I'm not saying another thing
till I see a lawyer.

14:52.058 --> 14:54.560
[ Buzzer sounds ]

14:54.560 --> 14:56.062
You think the guards
were in on it?

14:56.062 --> 14:57.688
Or the warden. Or both.

14:57.688 --> 14:59.982
You know who would know...

14:59.982 --> 15:01.484
Oh, absolutely not.

15:01.484 --> 15:04.028
This is his prison.
He's been helpful in the past.

15:04.028 --> 15:06.280
This is because
you jinxed us.

15:07.323 --> 15:08.991
[ Buzzer sounds ]

15:13.996 --> 15:16.624
It's my favorite
law‐enforcement officers!

15:16.624 --> 15:18.668
Wait. Don't tell me.
I have a son.

15:18.668 --> 15:20.086
[ Chuckling ]
I always wanted a boy.

15:20.086 --> 15:21.212
This isn't about you.

15:21.212 --> 15:23.172
Oh, you're seeing
other criminals. I'm hurt.

15:23.172 --> 15:24.632
What the hell
happened to you?

15:24.632 --> 15:27.009
Well, it turns out that you
snitch on one lifer too many,

15:27.009 --> 15:28.302
everybody turns on you.

15:28.302 --> 15:31.222
It's like junior high school
all over again.

15:31.222 --> 15:34.892
Oscar, are you familiar with
an inmate named Levi Lincoln?

15:34.892 --> 15:38.312
I am, and I know some
rather shocking things

15:38.312 --> 15:41.107
about Mr. Lincoln,
but it'll cost you.

15:41.107 --> 15:43.484
He's paying a double to serve
his time for him. We know.

15:43.484 --> 15:46.195
What we don't know
is who helped him.

15:46.195 --> 15:48.614
Well, I'll tell you
everything I know...

15:48.614 --> 15:50.992
but you have to get me
out of this prison.

15:50.992 --> 15:52.785
‐Forget it.
‐Given who I've pissed off,

15:52.785 --> 15:55.705
I'm looking at spending
the rest of my life here,

15:55.705 --> 15:57.790
in protective custody,
alone,

15:57.790 --> 16:00.751
with no one to talk to
but myself.

16:00.751 --> 16:03.337
I am concerned
for my sanity.

16:03.337 --> 16:05.464
So you want
a prison transfer.

16:05.464 --> 16:08.050
A letter of support from a cop
would go a long way.

16:08.050 --> 16:09.677
Fine.
I'll write a letter.

16:09.677 --> 16:12.013
Oh, that is so sweet,
but weren't you arrested

16:12.013 --> 16:14.098
for trying to murder
another police officer?

16:14.098 --> 16:16.184
I was exonerated!
You know that!

16:16.184 --> 16:17.351
I know, but still.

16:17.351 --> 16:18.769
Detective Harper?

16:18.769 --> 16:20.438
Sure.
Where do I send it?

16:23.399 --> 16:24.859
I know you know because ‐‐

16:24.859 --> 16:26.944
[ Cellphone ringing ]

16:26.944 --> 16:28.070
Hello?

16:28.070 --> 16:29.906
Randy: <i>Hey!</i>
<i>It's skip tracer Randy!</i>

16:29.906 --> 16:31.532
Randy, I know
you're a skip tracer.

16:31.532 --> 16:33.242
You don't have to tell me
every time.

16:33.242 --> 16:35.077
<i>You never know.</i>
<i>People are forgetful.</i>

16:35.077 --> 16:36.871
Did you get any information
on Jason Wyler?

16:36.871 --> 16:38.206
<i>Yes, sir, I did.</i>

16:38.206 --> 16:39.999
<i>Born in Chicago, 1984.</i>

16:39.999 --> 16:42.501
<i>Married Bailey Nune, 2016.</i>

16:42.501 --> 16:44.462
<i>Convicted of</i>
<i>embezzlement, 2019.</i>

16:44.462 --> 16:46.881
<i>He served two and a half years</i>
<i>of a six‐year sentence</i>

16:46.881 --> 16:49.133
<i>at Lompoc and was paroled</i>
<i>last week.</i>

16:49.133 --> 16:51.552
That's it? No other arrests
or complaints against him?

16:51.552 --> 16:52.678
<i>I gave you all I've got.</i>

16:52.678 --> 16:54.055
<i>I'll invoice you</i>
<i>for my services.</i>

16:54.055 --> 16:55.223
<i>Randy out!</i>

16:55.223 --> 16:56.307
[ <i>Click, beeping</i> ]

16:56.307 --> 16:57.808
[ Cellphone clicks ]

16:57.808 --> 17:00.269
Who's Jason Wyler?
None of your business.

17:00.269 --> 17:03.397
I can help you a lot more
than "skip tracer Randy."

17:03.397 --> 17:06.275
You want the real scoop
on this Jason character...

17:06.275 --> 17:08.194
come holla at your boy.

17:08.194 --> 17:12.406
"Oscar Hutchinson has
provided limited assistance

17:12.406 --> 17:14.200
to the LAPD
on several cases."

17:14.200 --> 17:15.368
Oh, that's sweet.

17:15.368 --> 17:17.036
Now, which
prison personnel

17:17.036 --> 17:19.914
did Levi pay
to pull off this switch?

17:19.914 --> 17:22.959
The warden.
And four guards ‐‐

17:22.959 --> 17:26.420
Morrison, Clark,
Hobson, and Lane.

17:26.420 --> 17:27.922
Thank you.

17:27.922 --> 17:29.340
[ Paper rustling ]

17:29.340 --> 17:33.010
Oh, and, uh, I faxed this to
our station, not your lawyer.

17:33.010 --> 17:34.095
[ Buzzer sounds ]

17:34.095 --> 17:36.055
That's just mean!

17:36.055 --> 17:38.766
The guy in jail is a fake.
Levi paid him to do his time.

17:38.766 --> 17:40.893
Well, we got several
911 calls about a man

17:40.893 --> 17:42.270
parachuting near Echo Park,

17:42.270 --> 17:43.771
but he was gone by the time
the police got there.

17:43.771 --> 17:44.981
Any idea where he went?

17:44.981 --> 17:46.774
No. We're pulling footage,
but no hits yet.

17:46.774 --> 17:48.276
I tracked the Cessna's
flight path.

17:48.276 --> 17:50.987
It took off from Sonoma,
home to, among other things,

17:50.987 --> 17:52.947
one of Levi's many estates.

17:52.947 --> 17:55.324
Local police checked it out,
found the back yard dug up.

17:55.324 --> 17:57.702
That's where he got
the gold bars.

17:57.702 --> 17:59.870
So he hires someone
to do his time,

17:59.870 --> 18:02.498
heads south of the border,
finds an out‐of‐the‐way place

18:02.498 --> 18:03.833
where no one will
recognize him.

18:03.833 --> 18:05.918
But he runs out of money,
and he knows he has gold

18:05.918 --> 18:07.962
stashed
at the Sonoma house.

18:07.962 --> 18:09.964
And he knows he can't board
a commercial flight, so he flies

18:09.964 --> 18:12.592
the Cessna, has engine trouble,
and here we are.

18:12.592 --> 18:14.802
The rich.
They live just like us.

18:14.802 --> 18:17.138
So you're Levi.
Where to next?

18:18.556 --> 18:19.932
Well, he still needs money.

18:19.932 --> 18:22.643
So if he hid gold bricks
in his vacation home,

18:22.643 --> 18:24.645
what are we gonna find
in his mansion in L. A.?

18:24.645 --> 18:27.440
Check it out.
On it.

18:27.440 --> 18:29.025
[ Vehicle doors closing ]

18:29.025 --> 18:30.985
[ Knock on door ]
Tim: Police. Open up.

18:32.695 --> 18:33.946
Can I help you?

18:33.946 --> 18:35.823
We're looking for
the homeowner, Mr. Lincoln.

18:35.823 --> 18:37.241
Mr. Lincoln's in prison.

18:37.241 --> 18:39.660
I'm taking care of his house
while he's away.

18:39.660 --> 18:42.538
Man in distance:
Hurry up! Hurry up!

18:44.206 --> 18:47.043
[ Whispering ]
Is ‐‐ Is he here?

18:47.043 --> 18:50.254
[ Whispering ] Back yard.
He's got Alfredo.

18:50.254 --> 18:51.422
[ Guns unholstering ]

18:51.422 --> 18:52.590
Ma'am, come here.

18:52.590 --> 18:53.799
Step outside.

18:53.799 --> 18:57.345
♪♪

18:57.345 --> 18:59.889
Man: Let's go. Come on.

18:59.889 --> 19:03.267
Dig! Faster!
Let's go, idiot!

19:03.267 --> 19:05.186
Hurry up!

19:05.186 --> 19:08.314
Come on!
Get the damn bag out.

19:08.314 --> 19:10.191
Come on. Faster!

19:10.191 --> 19:12.360
♪♪

19:12.360 --> 19:13.986
[ Gunshots ]

19:13.986 --> 19:16.280
♪♪

19:16.280 --> 19:18.574
7‐Adam‐100. Shots fired
at our location.

19:18.574 --> 19:20.076
Send backup and airship.

19:20.076 --> 19:26.457
♪♪

19:26.457 --> 19:28.125
[ Dog barking ]

19:28.125 --> 19:29.669
♪♪

19:29.669 --> 19:31.545
[ Engine starts and revs ]

19:34.173 --> 19:36.425
Control, 7‐Adam‐100.
Suspect is escaping

19:36.425 --> 19:39.136
on a black motorcycle,
headed east on Acorn.

19:42.264 --> 19:44.558
Levi got away, but we know
he's still desperate for money.

19:44.558 --> 19:45.976
We've compiled a list
of all of his acquaintances

19:45.976 --> 19:47.353
and potential money sources
across L. A. ‐‐

19:47.353 --> 19:48.521
anywhere he might
possibly show up.

19:48.521 --> 19:50.314
We should put a unit on
everyone. Squeeze him out.

19:50.314 --> 19:51.982
[ Cellphone buzzing ]
Alright. Send me that list.

19:51.982 --> 19:53.776
I'll use it to brief
the midnight shift.

19:53.776 --> 19:55.277
I'm sorry.
Uh, excuse me.

19:55.277 --> 19:56.445
Hello?

19:56.445 --> 19:58.364
Lucy,
it's Ashley McGrady.

19:58.364 --> 20:00.574
We met at my father's
retirement party.

20:00.574 --> 20:01.826
<i>Is this a good time?</i>

20:01.826 --> 20:04.787
Uh, yeah. Hey.
What's going on?

20:04.787 --> 20:05.996
<i>I have a problem.</i>

20:05.996 --> 20:09.667
I like Tim.
[ Sighs ] A lot.

20:09.667 --> 20:12.628
But his dog makes me
super nervous,

20:12.628 --> 20:15.047
and I‐I know
he was yours first.

20:15.047 --> 20:17.341
So...why did you
give him away?

20:17.341 --> 20:19.093
Was he too aggressive?

20:19.093 --> 20:21.679
No! Not at all.
I‐I mean, my living situation

20:21.679 --> 20:24.223
just wasn't suited
to having a pet.

20:24.223 --> 20:26.892
Uh, but Kojo
is the sweetest guy.

20:26.892 --> 20:29.895
I mean, do you ‐‐
do you not like dogs?

20:29.895 --> 20:33.190
I had a bad experience
when I was a kid.

20:33.190 --> 20:34.734
<i>I‐I totally get it.</i>

20:34.734 --> 20:37.903
Listen. Think about it this way.
Kojo is just like ‐‐

20:37.903 --> 20:40.489
Well, I‐I mean, he's
kind of just like Tim.

20:40.489 --> 20:43.200
He's big, gruff, a whole lot
of bark, but, you know,

20:43.200 --> 20:46.162
underneath all of it,
he's a ‐‐ he's a sweetheart.

20:46.162 --> 20:49.373
You know, you should, um, you
should tell Tim how you feel.

20:49.373 --> 20:51.500
No way. Never ask a man
to choose

20:51.500 --> 20:53.669
between his dog
and his girlfriend.

20:53.669 --> 20:56.338
There's a whole genre of country
songs that warn about that.

20:56.338 --> 20:57.423
[ Chuckles ]

20:57.423 --> 20:59.467
‐Anyway, I'm sorry to vent.
‐No.

20:59.467 --> 21:01.260
<i>I'll let you</i>
<i>go back to your night.</i>

21:01.260 --> 21:02.386
<i>Thank you.</i>

21:02.386 --> 21:03.846
[ <i>Click, beep</i> ]
Oh. Oh.

21:03.846 --> 21:05.139
Are you Officer Chen?

21:05.139 --> 21:06.640
Uh, yeah, I am. Hi.

21:06.640 --> 21:08.559
Chris Sanford, DA's office.

21:08.559 --> 21:12.146
Did you cite out a drug dealer
named Tyler Stent earlier today?

21:12.146 --> 21:13.564
Yes. I did.

21:13.564 --> 21:16.025
But Tyler is a juvenile
on his first defense,

21:16.025 --> 21:18.068
so I wouldn't just label him
a "drug dealer."

21:18.068 --> 21:19.862
I know.
Your arrest report

21:19.862 --> 21:22.239
detailed his tale of woe
at length.

21:22.239 --> 21:24.158
Honestly, it's a good thing
this isn't going to trial.

21:24.158 --> 21:26.327
You pretty much just handed
the defense their case.

21:26.327 --> 21:27.745
I handed them the truth.

21:27.745 --> 21:29.288
[ Scoffs ]
You're not really that naive.

21:29.288 --> 21:30.706
No, I'm not.

21:30.706 --> 21:32.249
I'm trying
to protect this city.

21:32.249 --> 21:34.126
And because of you,
a criminal who was selling

21:34.126 --> 21:36.170
dangerous substances
is back on our streets.

21:36.170 --> 21:39.048
Really? So you think putting
a 16‐year‐old into juvie

21:39.048 --> 21:40.382
for a nonviolent offense

21:40.382 --> 21:42.510
is gonna turn the tide
in the war on drugs?

21:42.510 --> 21:43.969
<i>Now</i> who's being naive?
[ Scoffs ]

21:43.969 --> 21:46.013
How long have you been
on the job, Chris?

21:47.515 --> 21:48.641
Four months.

21:48.641 --> 21:50.017
Mm.
But that's not relevant.

21:50.017 --> 21:52.686
Okay. So, tell you what. Let's
give it a year and a half,

21:52.686 --> 21:54.438
and then you can come
and criticize my work.

21:54.438 --> 21:56.524
Alright?
Nice to meet you, Chris.

21:56.524 --> 21:59.360
♪♪

21:59.360 --> 22:02.154
‐Good night. Get some sleep.
‐Thanks.

22:02.154 --> 22:03.656
Get home safe.

22:03.656 --> 22:05.407
[ Insects chirping ]

22:06.951 --> 22:08.661
[ Engine starts ]

22:10.913 --> 22:13.082
[ Bailey sighs, keys jingling ]

22:13.082 --> 22:15.000
[ Engine sputtering ]

22:17.545 --> 22:19.880
[ Scoffs ] Perfect.

22:19.880 --> 22:21.006
[ Keys thud ]

22:21.006 --> 22:22.091
Just what I need.

22:22.091 --> 22:23.300
[ Door opens ]

22:27.179 --> 22:28.889
[ Door closes ]

22:30.641 --> 22:32.351
[ Sighs ]

22:32.351 --> 22:34.103
[ Latch clicks ]

22:39.024 --> 22:40.276
[ Sighs ]

22:40.276 --> 22:42.027
[ Glass bottles
clanking in distance ]

22:49.451 --> 22:50.703
[ <i>Line ringing</i> ]

22:50.703 --> 22:52.288
[ Cellphone ringing ]

22:58.127 --> 23:00.504
[ Click ]
Hello?

23:00.504 --> 23:02.590
I'm sorry for reaching out.
I just ‐‐

23:02.590 --> 23:04.258
I didn't know
who else to call.

23:05.384 --> 23:06.719
You alright?

23:06.719 --> 23:10.014
Yeah. I'm fine.
It's just been...a day.

23:11.932 --> 23:14.101
I know I'm the last person
you want to hear from right now,

23:14.101 --> 23:15.936
but I feel like

23:15.936 --> 23:19.607
if you and I just sat down,
I could explain.

23:19.607 --> 23:23.193
♪♪

23:23.193 --> 23:27.740
I really hope that's true,
but, um...

23:27.740 --> 23:29.325
I can't do it tonight.

23:29.325 --> 23:31.660
<i>I just need a little time</i>
<i>to get on top of how I feel.</i>

23:31.660 --> 23:34.371
You, um...

23:34.371 --> 23:35.831
broke my heart a little.

23:35.831 --> 23:36.999
[ Voice breaking ] I know.

23:36.999 --> 23:39.293
I would do anything
to take it back.

23:39.293 --> 23:45.007
♪♪

23:45.007 --> 23:47.551
I'll call you.

23:47.551 --> 23:50.638
[ <i>Click, beeping</i> ]

23:50.638 --> 23:52.222
[ Sobs ]

23:52.222 --> 23:55.392
[ Laughter,
indistinct conversations ]

23:55.392 --> 23:58.646
[ Laughter ]

23:58.646 --> 24:00.105
Hey, guys.
[ Door closes ]

24:00.105 --> 24:02.024
Your husband cannot
hold his liquor.

24:02.024 --> 24:04.818
Uh, I am fine.
Don't listen to him.

24:04.818 --> 24:06.278
Is James staying over
for dinner?

24:06.278 --> 24:07.488
Oh!
We're gonna get pizza.

24:07.488 --> 24:09.323
Mm. Ah, and ‐‐
and some garlic knots.

24:09.323 --> 24:11.533
Yes.
And garlic knots!

24:11.533 --> 24:14.161
Yep, yep, yep.
[ Exhales deeply ]

24:14.161 --> 24:16.956
So, what are you
gonna do with yourself

24:16.956 --> 24:18.624
for the next six months?

24:18.624 --> 24:21.669
I don't know.
S‐Spend more time with Jack.

24:21.669 --> 24:23.212
Maybe get rid of the nanny.

24:23.212 --> 24:24.421
Over your dead body.

24:24.421 --> 24:25.798
[ Laughs ] Okay.

24:25.798 --> 24:27.925
Well, I could
always use your help

24:27.925 --> 24:29.593
over at
the community center.

24:29.593 --> 24:32.513
I mean, people come in with
legal questions all the time.

24:32.513 --> 24:34.348
Just yesterday,
a lady came in,

24:34.348 --> 24:37.101
didn't know whether her sister
should take a plea deal.

24:37.101 --> 24:39.770
Oh, man. Do not get me started
on plea deals ‐‐

24:39.770 --> 24:41.355
how they
disproportionately affect

24:41.355 --> 24:42.606
people in marginalized
communities.

24:42.606 --> 24:44.024
Yes. Exactly!

24:44.024 --> 24:45.693
I know.
Exactly.

24:45.693 --> 24:48.696
[ Cellphone rings, beeps ]
What's up?

24:48.696 --> 24:50.739
Lopez: <i>Your boyfriend</i>
<i>is at my house.</i>

24:50.739 --> 24:51.907
What?

24:51.907 --> 24:54.076
Yeah. He and Wesley went out
drinking together.

24:54.076 --> 24:55.744
See? That‐‐ That's
what I'm saying!

24:55.744 --> 24:57.788
‐I know! A hundred percent!
‐That's what I'm saying!

24:57.788 --> 24:59.540
Are they watching
a game?

24:59.540 --> 25:01.709
Mm, no.
Fixing the judicial system.

25:01.709 --> 25:03.377
Luckily,
Jack is at my mom's.

25:03.377 --> 25:05.170
We're ordering some pizzas.
Want to come over?

25:05.170 --> 25:06.630
[ Alarm beeps, door opens ]
On my way.

25:06.630 --> 25:08.424
Lucy: Tim!
Hold up a second.

25:08.424 --> 25:10.175
Hey, did something
come in on Levi?

25:10.175 --> 25:14.596
Uh, no. Uh, you know
that call I took earlier?

25:14.596 --> 25:17.182
It was ‐‐
It was Ashley.

25:17.182 --> 25:18.809
Why is my girlfriend
calling you?

25:18.809 --> 25:21.228
She wanted to know
if Kojo was a dangerous dog,

25:21.228 --> 25:23.272
'cause you told her
he used to be mine.

25:23.272 --> 25:25.315
Okay.
That's ridiculous.

25:25.315 --> 25:27.651
I mean, he growled at her
a few times,

25:27.651 --> 25:29.028
but he's just
getting used to her.

25:29.028 --> 25:30.195
I‐It's not a big deal.

25:30.195 --> 25:32.114
W‐‐ It is to her.

25:32.114 --> 25:34.992
And you're so concerned
about my love life because?

25:34.992 --> 25:37.119
Because I don't want to drive
around on patrol with you

25:37.119 --> 25:39.663
while you are moping
about screwing this up.

25:39.663 --> 25:43.042
Look, if you like this girl,
you should listen to her.

25:48.088 --> 25:50.382
When have I ever moped?

25:50.382 --> 25:52.634
I don't even know how.
Mm‐hmm.

25:52.634 --> 25:55.095
[ Cellphone ringing ]

25:58.348 --> 25:59.725
[ Click ]

26:01.268 --> 26:04.396
‐Hello?
‐Johnny? It's Oscar.

26:04.396 --> 26:06.982
Calling a cop
on a contraband cellphone

26:06.982 --> 26:08.567
is not the smartest.

26:08.567 --> 26:10.110
Fine.
I could just hang up

26:10.110 --> 26:13.238
rather than tell you what I
found out about your boy Jason.

26:16.450 --> 26:17.659
What did you find out?

26:17.659 --> 26:18.994
<i>First things first.</i>

26:18.994 --> 26:21.080
[ Grunts ]

26:21.080 --> 26:23.916
I need a letter faxed to my
lawyer's office by 8:00 a. m.

26:23.916 --> 26:26.752
supporting my appeal to
change prisons for my safety.

26:26.752 --> 26:28.253
I thought
I wasn't good enough.

26:28.253 --> 26:31.090
Beggars can't be choosers.
Do we have a deal?

26:32.132 --> 26:33.675
Yeah.
Now tell me what you found.

26:33.675 --> 26:36.637
Okay. I talked to a couple
of buddies of mine in Lompoc.

26:36.637 --> 26:40.432
Apparently, Jason Wyler is the
most charming man on the planet,

26:40.432 --> 26:42.309
and he's a cold‐blooded
manipulator.

26:42.309 --> 26:43.852
Yeah,
but is he dangerous?

26:43.852 --> 26:45.771
I mean, he's serving time
for embezzlement.

26:45.771 --> 26:47.022
He wasn't violent.

26:47.022 --> 26:48.649
<i>From what I've heard,</i>
<i>he doesn't have to be.</i>

26:48.649 --> 26:50.234
He whispers
in all the right ears,

26:50.234 --> 26:53.153
and whoever is his enemy ends up
on the wrong end of a shank...

26:53.153 --> 26:55.239
with no way
to trace it back to him.

26:55.239 --> 26:57.157
[ Keys clank, switch clicks ]

27:02.955 --> 27:04.540
[ Floorboard creaks ]

27:04.540 --> 27:10.170
♪♪

27:10.170 --> 27:11.880
[ Floorboard creaks ]

27:11.880 --> 27:17.052
♪♪

27:17.052 --> 27:18.554
[ Dog barking in distance ]

27:18.554 --> 27:25.102
♪♪

27:25.102 --> 27:31.692
♪♪

27:31.692 --> 27:33.193
[ Hinges creak ]

27:33.193 --> 27:34.736
[ Switch clicks ]

27:34.736 --> 27:41.827
♪♪

27:41.827 --> 27:48.917
♪♪

27:48.917 --> 27:50.669
[ Hinges creak ]

27:50.669 --> 27:59.678
♪♪

27:59.678 --> 28:01.388
[ Exhales deeply ]

28:01.388 --> 28:09.438
♪♪

28:09.438 --> 28:17.529
♪♪

28:21.199 --> 28:23.327
So, alright.
Here's where we're at.

28:23.327 --> 28:25.746
So, we had eyes on Lincoln's
business associates

28:25.746 --> 28:27.331
and possible money sources

28:27.331 --> 28:29.207
all last night,
but Levi never showed.

28:29.207 --> 28:32.336
Well, maybe he left town without
getting his hands on any money.

28:32.336 --> 28:33.962
That doesn't seem likely.

28:33.962 --> 28:36.298
There's a certain standard
of living he likes to uphold.

28:36.298 --> 28:38.675
So we keep watching his rich
friends and hope for the best.

28:39.509 --> 28:43.263
You know, there is one rich
friend we're <i>not</i> watching.

28:43.263 --> 28:44.681
His double ‐‐ Lamar Sheff.

28:44.681 --> 28:47.100
Lincoln paid Sheff $5 million
up front to do the time,

28:47.100 --> 28:48.936
and there's no way
the double's family

28:48.936 --> 28:51.063
could spend it without
throwing up red flags.

28:51.063 --> 28:53.190
Sheff's wife
lives in Whittier.

28:53.190 --> 28:55.484
Harper, Nolan,
go check it out.

28:55.484 --> 28:57.945
First thing we have to do is
take your felony off the table.

28:57.945 --> 29:00.572
A felony conviction can be
a life sentence to poverty.

29:00.572 --> 29:02.449
It'll affect your
future job opportunities,

29:02.449 --> 29:04.368
applying for loans.

29:04.368 --> 29:05.827
Oh, man, so I'm screwed,
aren't I?

29:05.827 --> 29:07.537
Not if we use Prop 47.

29:07.537 --> 29:09.539
Wait. But that's for
personal drug use only.

29:09.539 --> 29:11.416
Yeah, but it's harder
to prove a sales case.

29:11.416 --> 29:13.919
And don't forget ‐‐ we have
a friendly arresting officer.

29:13.919 --> 29:15.754
This will get knocked back
to a misdemeanor possession,

29:15.754 --> 29:17.881
which means
no jail time for you.

29:17.881 --> 29:19.216
For real?
So I'm ‐‐ I'm good?

29:19.216 --> 29:21.051
Ha! Not even close.

29:21.051 --> 29:23.136
That's the easy part.
Now comes the hard.

29:23.136 --> 29:26.390
From this day on, you are here
every day after school, okay?

29:26.390 --> 29:27.641
We're gonna review
your homework,

29:27.641 --> 29:29.518
and if there's anything
that you want to talk about,

29:29.518 --> 29:30.811
we'll do that, too.
[ Door opens ]

29:30.811 --> 29:32.646
And you're getting a job.

29:32.646 --> 29:34.481
[ Door closes ]

29:36.024 --> 29:38.360
Curtis.
[ Clears throat ]

29:38.360 --> 29:39.444
How you doing?

29:39.444 --> 29:42.030
Me? I'm alright.
I'll be a whole lot better

29:42.030 --> 29:44.658
once Lil' Man
hollers at me outside.

29:44.658 --> 29:47.536
Anything you want to say
to Tyler, you can tell us.

29:47.536 --> 29:48.704
And who's "us"?

29:48.704 --> 29:50.038
I'm part of Tyler's
legal team.

29:50.038 --> 29:52.082
Legal team.
[ Chuckles ]

29:52.082 --> 29:54.251
Alright. For real?

29:54.251 --> 29:55.836
Okay.
[ Clears throat ]

29:55.836 --> 29:57.462
So, check this out,
lawyer.

29:57.462 --> 29:59.589
Your client here entered
a verbal commitment with me

29:59.589 --> 30:01.967
over the sale
of certain items.

30:01.967 --> 30:04.970
Those items are now lost.
He owes me restitution.

30:04.970 --> 30:07.639
He's getting a job, but he'll
need some time to pay you back.

30:07.639 --> 30:09.933
With interest.
By tomorrow.

30:09.933 --> 30:12.144
Thirty days.
No interest.

30:13.729 --> 30:14.855
Excuse me?

30:14.855 --> 30:17.566
Curtis, do not
make this a thing.

30:17.566 --> 30:21.570
Aw. Nah. It's too late
for all that, James.

30:21.570 --> 30:23.572
Now, listen.

30:23.572 --> 30:26.241
I came in here alone
out of respect.

30:26.241 --> 30:27.951
In here,
this is your world.

30:27.951 --> 30:30.537
Out there, that's mine.

30:31.580 --> 30:33.665
I'll be seeing you,
Lil' Man.

30:34.958 --> 30:36.460
[ Exhales sharply,
sniffles ]

30:36.460 --> 30:38.045
We got to find a place
for him to lay low

30:38.045 --> 30:39.880
while we work this out.

30:39.880 --> 30:43.008
I can, uh ‐‐ I can take him to
his aunt's place in Covina.

30:43.008 --> 30:45.260
Hey. Hey. Relax.
It's gonna be okay.

30:45.260 --> 30:46.887
But you got to go
to ground, okay?

30:46.887 --> 30:48.096
Stay off your phone.

30:48.096 --> 30:50.223
Don't tell anyone where you are.
You got it?

30:50.223 --> 30:52.768
[ Softly ] Yeah.

30:52.768 --> 30:54.644
[ Horn honks ]

30:57.230 --> 30:58.273
You okay?

30:58.273 --> 30:59.483
Yeah.

30:59.483 --> 31:02.110
Well, n‐no. Yes. No.

31:02.110 --> 31:04.654
[ Inhales sharply ]
I talked to Oscar last night.

31:04.654 --> 31:05.822
What the hell for?

31:05.822 --> 31:07.282
He got intel on Jason.

31:07.282 --> 31:08.700
The <i>real,</i>
from inside the prison.

31:08.700 --> 31:10.702
And it turns out this guy's
as much of a nightmare

31:10.702 --> 31:13.330
as Bailey hinted at.

31:13.330 --> 31:15.415
Well, it doesn't excuse her
not telling you,

31:15.415 --> 31:17.292
but it does explain it.

31:17.292 --> 31:19.044
She probably still hasn't
dealt with the trauma.

31:19.044 --> 31:21.588
So what do I do?
Do I just...let it slide?

31:21.588 --> 31:24.007
If ‐‐ If Jason is
as dangerous as he says,

31:24.007 --> 31:25.717
then he could go
back after Bailey.

31:25.717 --> 31:28.553
Yeah, but Bailey's not exactly
a damsel in distress.

31:28.553 --> 31:31.473
I mean, you remember what
she did to that Russian spy.

31:31.473 --> 31:33.850
If he does make a move,
my money's on Bailey.

31:34.935 --> 31:36.603
[ Lawn mower running ]

31:42.067 --> 31:43.401
[ Lawn mower stops ]

31:43.401 --> 31:44.820
Hey.

31:44.820 --> 31:47.155
What a, uh, nice surprise.

31:47.155 --> 31:49.658
Uh, I'm sorry.
I'm ‐‐ I'm all sweaty. Is ‐‐

31:49.658 --> 31:51.034
I know what you're doing.

31:51.034 --> 31:52.536
[ Chuckles ]
Mowing the lawn?

31:52.536 --> 31:53.954
Just stop with the games.

31:53.954 --> 31:56.998
Charming my co‐workers,
pretending you want a divorce?

31:56.998 --> 31:58.959
I'm not buying it,
not for one second.

31:58.959 --> 32:00.377
You were in my house!

32:00.377 --> 32:02.129
What? No, I wasn't.

32:02.129 --> 32:05.298
But you're right about one
thing ‐‐ I don't want a divorce.

32:05.298 --> 32:06.883
I want things to go back
to the way they were.

32:06.883 --> 32:09.803
Uh, which part?
The part where you shamed me,

32:09.803 --> 32:13.056
belittled me, tried to control
everything in my life?

32:13.056 --> 32:15.809
Okay. Look.
I‐I admit that I wasn't perfect.

32:15.809 --> 32:18.186
But you ‐‐ you needed help,
guidance, okay?

32:18.186 --> 32:20.272
E‐Everything that I did,
I did for you.

32:20.272 --> 32:21.857
You abused me, Jason!

32:21.857 --> 32:23.483
Oh, come on. I never laid
a finger on you!

32:23.483 --> 32:24.693
You didn't have to!

32:24.693 --> 32:27.279
You isolated me from
my family and friends!

32:27.279 --> 32:29.656
You made me think
it was all my fault!

32:29.656 --> 32:31.658
You gaslit me to the point
of a breakdown!

32:31.658 --> 32:33.577
[ Hushed ]
Could we talk about this later?

32:33.577 --> 32:36.079
Hell no!
We are talking about it now!

32:36.079 --> 32:38.373
When I left,
I was in pieces.

32:38.373 --> 32:40.167
And then I moved out here

32:40.167 --> 32:44.212
and I rebuilt my entire life
from scratch.

32:44.212 --> 32:46.173
I am not the same person
anymore.

32:46.173 --> 32:47.299
And neither am I!

32:47.299 --> 32:49.759
Shut up and listen to me.

32:49.759 --> 32:52.971
When I say I am not the same
person anymore, I mean it.

32:52.971 --> 32:54.723
And if you push me,

32:54.723 --> 32:58.935
I will push back harder
than you can imagine.

32:58.935 --> 33:00.520
Do you understand?

33:02.564 --> 33:05.400
Yeah. I understand.

33:06.985 --> 33:08.403
Good.

33:08.403 --> 33:11.781
Stay away from me.
Forever.

33:11.781 --> 33:15.285
♪♪

33:15.285 --> 33:17.495
[ Exhales deeply ]

33:22.876 --> 33:24.711
How much farther?
About five minutes.

33:24.711 --> 33:26.296
Man:
<i>7‐Adam‐15, be advised ‐‐</i>

33:26.296 --> 33:28.506
<i>Whittier police responded</i>
<i>to a 911 call</i>

33:28.506 --> 33:31.134
<i>about your suspect,</i>
<i>Levi Lincoln.</i>

33:31.134 --> 33:32.719
7‐Adam‐15.
Go ahead.

33:32.719 --> 33:35.347
<i>On‐scene detectives confirm</i>
<i>that suspect Levi Lincoln</i>

33:35.347 --> 33:37.390
<i>forced his way into a home</i>
<i>at gunpoint,</i>

33:37.390 --> 33:38.934
<i>forced a female victim,</i>
<i>Linda Sheff,</i>

33:38.934 --> 33:41.436
<i>to wire $4 million</i>
<i>to a Cayman Islands account.</i>

33:41.436 --> 33:43.521
[ Beep, static hisses ]
That's Lamar's wife.

33:43.521 --> 33:45.690
Cayman Islands means
he's fleeing the country.

33:45.690 --> 33:48.443
There's a private airfield
somewhere around here.

33:48.443 --> 33:50.570
Take your next right.
It's about a half‐mile east.

33:50.570 --> 33:52.822
Control, notify local PD.

33:52.822 --> 33:55.367
We believe suspect
is headed for Whittier Airstrip.

33:55.367 --> 33:57.786
Have them send backup,
and notify Sgt. Bradford.

33:57.786 --> 33:59.329
[ Engine revving ]

33:59.329 --> 34:05.502
♪♪

34:05.502 --> 34:07.837
Harper: Black motorcycle.
Nolan: Someone's at the plane.

34:07.837 --> 34:09.839
[ Engine revs ]
It's Levi.

34:09.839 --> 34:11.549
[ Siren chirping ]

34:11.549 --> 34:13.260
Gun.

34:13.260 --> 34:16.471
♪♪

34:16.471 --> 34:18.265
Control, taking handgun fire
from the suspect

34:18.265 --> 34:19.349
at Whittier Airstrip.

34:19.349 --> 34:21.518
We're pursuing on foot.

34:21.518 --> 34:23.895
[ Airplane passing ]

34:23.895 --> 34:30.277
♪♪

34:30.277 --> 34:31.361
[ Gunshots,
bullets ricocheting ]

34:31.361 --> 34:38.159
♪♪

34:38.159 --> 34:39.536
What's your plan, Levi?

34:39.536 --> 34:41.830
You're trapped,
and we got backup on the way.

34:41.830 --> 34:43.164
One problem at a time.

34:43.164 --> 34:45.875
All I got to do is get rid
of you two and get in my plane.

34:45.875 --> 34:47.168
I hate to break it
to you,

34:47.168 --> 34:49.129
but law enforcement
has airplanes, too ‐‐

34:49.129 --> 34:50.505
and this thing
called radar.

34:50.505 --> 34:53.216
Plus, getting rid of us
is gonna be a tall order.

34:53.216 --> 34:55.051
Yeah.
I've overcome bigger obstacles.

34:55.051 --> 35:03.560
♪♪

35:03.560 --> 35:07.022
[ Gunfire, bullets ricocheting ]

35:07.022 --> 35:11.443
♪♪

35:11.443 --> 35:13.653
You do realize
you're gonna spend

35:13.653 --> 35:16.197
twice as much time in prison
as you originally were.

35:16.197 --> 35:19.576
Was three years of freedom worth
the 10 extra?

35:19.576 --> 35:27.000
♪♪

35:27.000 --> 35:29.586
[ Gunfire, bullets ricocheting ]

35:29.586 --> 35:35.508
♪♪

35:35.508 --> 35:38.970
[ Radio chirps ]
Tim: <i>7‐Adam‐15.</i>
<i>7‐Adam‐100 arriving on scene.</i>

35:38.970 --> 35:41.139
What's your status?
We have the suspect pinned down
inside.

35:41.139 --> 35:43.475
We could use backup
at the side entrance.

35:43.475 --> 35:44.976
[ Static hisses ]

35:44.976 --> 35:47.020
[ Gunfire, bullets ricocheting ]

35:47.020 --> 35:51.691
♪♪

35:51.691 --> 35:53.693
[ Gun clicking ]

35:53.693 --> 35:55.320
Hi.

35:56.529 --> 35:57.739
Drop the gun.

35:57.739 --> 35:59.199
[ Airplane passing ]

35:59.199 --> 36:01.409
Control, suspect in custody.
We're Code 4.

36:01.409 --> 36:03.787
Fun fact ‐‐
It's gonna be a lot harder

36:03.787 --> 36:05.914
to buy your way out of this
with no money.

36:05.914 --> 36:07.791
[ Handcuffs clicking ]
Tell me about it.

36:07.791 --> 36:10.293
Being broke sucks.
[ Chuckles ]

36:10.293 --> 36:11.753
[ Exhales deeply ]

36:11.753 --> 36:13.797
[ Buzzer sounds ]

36:13.797 --> 36:15.465
[ Indistinct conversations ]

36:15.465 --> 36:16.549
Thank you.

36:16.549 --> 36:19.052
Yeah.
That should be everything.

36:19.052 --> 36:20.470
Officer Chen.

36:20.470 --> 36:22.055
[ Exhales sharply ]
You're back.

36:22.055 --> 36:23.807
Has it been a year and a half
already?

36:23.807 --> 36:26.726
Tyler Stent was just arrested
for armed robbery.

36:27.686 --> 36:29.938
He pointed a gun
at an elderly store owner,

36:29.938 --> 36:31.815
who then suffered
a heart attack.

36:31.815 --> 36:33.942
If she dies, I'm charging
your kid with murder.

36:33.942 --> 36:36.528
If you hadn't cited him out,
this wouldn't have happened.

36:36.528 --> 36:39.072
[ Buzzer sounds, door opens ]

36:43.410 --> 36:47.997
♪ Do you remember sounds
of autumn singing? ♪

36:47.997 --> 36:49.416
[ Siren chirping ]

36:49.416 --> 36:56.297
♪ But we have been dropping
like the flies we are ♪

36:56.297 --> 36:58.842
Driver, turn off your car
and place both hands

36:58.842 --> 37:01.261
out of the window.
[ Siren chirping ]

37:01.261 --> 37:03.096
What the hell?

37:03.096 --> 37:05.014
[ Music stops,
engine shuts off ]

37:05.014 --> 37:07.642
Driver, open the door
from the outside.

37:07.642 --> 37:09.644
Step out with your hands
above your head.

37:09.644 --> 37:12.647
[ Insects chirping,
dog barking in distance ]

37:12.647 --> 37:14.816
Step away from the vehicle.
What is going on?

37:14.816 --> 37:16.151
Ma'am, step away
from the vehicle!

37:16.151 --> 37:18.903
I haven't done anything wrong.
I'm LAFD.

37:18.903 --> 37:20.655
We'll tell you what's going on
in a second.

37:20.655 --> 37:22.574
Step away from the vehicle,
ma'am.

37:22.574 --> 37:25.952
I‐I didn't give you permission
to search my car.

37:25.952 --> 37:28.580
What is happening?
Why am I...

37:28.580 --> 37:30.206
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

37:30.206 --> 37:32.250
Wait. That isn't mine.
You have a right
to remain silent.

37:32.250 --> 37:33.960
Anything you say can
and will be used against you.

37:33.960 --> 37:37.714
It was my husband.
He's framing me.

37:42.343 --> 37:45.180
[ "Jingle Bells" playing ]

37:45.180 --> 37:46.222
Nolan?

37:51.311 --> 37:53.438
[ Buzzer sounds, door opens ]

37:59.152 --> 38:00.361
You got two minutes.

38:00.361 --> 38:01.446
Thank you.

38:01.446 --> 38:02.489
You okay?

38:02.489 --> 38:03.823
No.
I'm pissed.

38:03.823 --> 38:05.033
Jason set me up.

38:05.033 --> 38:06.451
Yes. I know.
I know.

38:06.451 --> 38:08.787
His fragile little ego never
could handle being challenged.

38:08.787 --> 38:10.288
I should have
seen this coming.

38:10.288 --> 38:11.706
This is not your fault.

38:11.706 --> 38:14.626
I confronted him at work.
I embarrassed him.

38:14.626 --> 38:17.337
I knew he'd retaliate,
but I didn't care.

38:17.337 --> 38:20.548
I just wanted to show him
that I wasn't scared.

38:20.548 --> 38:22.383
[ Sighs ]
I was <i>so</i> stupid.

38:22.383 --> 38:25.220
No. You were right
to stand up to him.

38:25.220 --> 38:26.596
There's no winning.

38:26.596 --> 38:28.348
I run.
He tracks me down.

38:28.348 --> 38:30.475
I fight back.
He takes my career.

38:30.475 --> 38:32.185
If I'm convicted
on a drug charge,

38:32.185 --> 38:33.686
they'll throw me off
the job.

38:33.686 --> 38:34.813
And he knows it.

38:34.813 --> 38:37.899
He's taking everything
that matters to me.

38:37.899 --> 38:40.401
It's what he does.

38:40.401 --> 38:42.987
He thinks if I'll get
low enough, I'll go back to him.

38:42.987 --> 38:45.323
Okay.
Well, that's never gonna happen.

38:45.323 --> 38:47.575
How much is my bail?
I can pay you back.

38:48.493 --> 38:50.954
Okay. Well, it's not quite
that simple.

38:50.954 --> 38:53.039
The amount of cocaine
they found in your car ‐‐

38:53.039 --> 38:54.749
They're gonna charge you
with a felony.

38:54.749 --> 38:56.459
That means you're gonna
have to wait for a judge

38:56.459 --> 38:57.460
to set your bail.

38:57.460 --> 39:00.296
[ Sighs ]

39:00.296 --> 39:01.923
And how long
will that take?

39:01.923 --> 39:04.509
Hopefully a day,
maybe two.

39:04.509 --> 39:06.052
But don't worry.

39:06.052 --> 39:08.096
While you're in here,
I'm going to fix it.

39:08.096 --> 39:09.848
I can't ask you
to do that.

39:09.848 --> 39:12.517
You don't have to.
I'm doing it because I love you.

39:13.560 --> 39:15.395
Still?

39:15.395 --> 39:17.647
Yes.
Still.

39:17.647 --> 39:19.691
♪♪

39:19.691 --> 39:22.777
But that doesn't get us
anywhere near to good.

39:22.777 --> 39:26.948
But nobody screws with you
and gets away with it.

39:27.907 --> 39:33.538
♪ I hear the drizzle
of the rain ♪

39:33.538 --> 39:35.039
♪ Like a memory... ♪

39:35.039 --> 39:37.166
Tyler, what happened?
We had a deal.

39:37.166 --> 39:39.002
I had to get Curtis
his money.

39:39.002 --> 39:41.004
No.
We were coming up with a plan.

39:41.004 --> 39:42.839
Why didn't you just listen
to us?

39:42.839 --> 39:45.466
I'm sorry.
I panicked.

39:45.466 --> 39:47.886
I...
Is the lady gonna be alright?

39:47.886 --> 39:49.137
♪♪

39:49.137 --> 39:50.555
We don't know yet.

39:50.555 --> 39:53.892
Come on.
Move it along.

39:53.892 --> 39:55.101
♪♪

39:55.101 --> 40:00.773
♪ And from the shelter
of my mind ♪

40:00.773 --> 40:06.154
♪ Through the window
of my eyes ♪

40:06.154 --> 40:08.197
♪ I gaze beyond... ♪

40:08.197 --> 40:10.116
Voice:
<i>Disarm system now.</i>

40:10.116 --> 40:11.951
[ Monitor beeping ]
Hey, buddy.

40:11.951 --> 40:13.244
[ Dog growls ]

40:13.244 --> 40:17.498
♪ ...to England,
where my heart lies ♪

40:17.498 --> 40:19.751
[ Monitor beeps, dog barks ]
<i>Disarmed. Ready to arm.</i>

40:19.751 --> 40:22.503
[ Sighs ]
This is a terrible idea.

40:22.503 --> 40:24.088
No.
It's gonna be great, okay?

40:24.088 --> 40:25.965
I want you to feel
as comfortable here

40:25.965 --> 40:27.342
as you do at home.

40:27.342 --> 40:30.261
Look, Carl from the K9 unit said
that dogs respond positively

40:30.261 --> 40:31.930
to people who display control,
okay?

40:31.930 --> 40:32.972
They're pack animals.

40:32.972 --> 40:34.515
They know when they see
a leader.

40:34.515 --> 40:37.477
I know this is scary,
but I'm right here with you.

40:37.477 --> 40:39.604
And I promise you,
you're gonna ‐‐

40:39.604 --> 40:42.023
you're gonna love him
if you just give him a chance.

40:42.023 --> 40:44.692
[ Dog whines ]

40:44.692 --> 40:48.655
♪ There but for the grace of you
go I ♪

40:48.655 --> 40:49.906
Sit.

40:49.906 --> 40:52.283
[ Dog whines ]

40:52.283 --> 40:54.994
Too nice.
Just boss him around a little.

40:54.994 --> 40:57.205
♪♪

40:57.205 --> 40:58.206
Sit.

40:58.206 --> 41:00.833
♪♪

41:00.833 --> 41:03.795
Down.
[ Exhales sharply, laughs ]

41:03.795 --> 41:05.630
♪♪

41:05.630 --> 41:07.715
Hey, hey.
[ Laughing ] That's my job.

41:07.715 --> 41:10.885
Okay, Kojo.
[ Laughing ] One step at a time.

41:10.885 --> 41:13.054
♪♪

41:13.054 --> 41:16.641
[ Siren wailing in distance ]

41:20.979 --> 41:22.855
It's, uh, John, right?

41:22.855 --> 41:24.732
Good to see you again.

41:24.732 --> 41:26.067
No need for the act.

41:26.067 --> 41:28.069
You planted those drugs.

41:28.069 --> 41:29.737
What?
Drugs?

41:29.737 --> 41:30.989
Wh‐‐ Uh, whoa, whoa.
Uh, rewind.

41:30.989 --> 41:32.448
I don't know
what you're talking about.

41:32.448 --> 41:34.158
Yeah, you do.

41:35.410 --> 41:38.162
Bailey's sitting in a jail cell
right now because of you.

41:38.162 --> 41:40.248
She is?

41:40.248 --> 41:42.792
Oh, God.
That's, uh, horrible.

41:42.792 --> 41:44.544
No.

41:44.544 --> 41:47.088
It's exactly
what you wanted.

41:48.172 --> 41:49.674
Well, of course
it isn't.

41:49.674 --> 41:52.427
But, you know,
I got to say,

41:52.427 --> 41:54.971
hearing that she's finally
facing some consequences

41:54.971 --> 41:56.764
for her actions, well...

41:57.932 --> 42:01.102
...it does well
for my spirit.

42:01.102 --> 42:03.771
♪♪

42:03.771 --> 42:07.734
You really can't
let her be happy, can you?

42:07.734 --> 42:10.903
Couldn't stand that she
didn't need you anymore.

42:10.903 --> 42:13.364
Well...

42:13.364 --> 42:15.616
Well, your time is over.

42:15.616 --> 42:18.036
I know who you are now.

42:18.036 --> 42:19.704
And I'm coming for you.

42:29.839 --> 42:39.223
♪♪

42:39.223 --> 42:48.733
♪♪

42:48.733 --> 42:58.242
♪♪
